  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_1435",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Publicly Verifiable Zero Knowledge from (Collapsing) Blockchains",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Alessandra Scafuro",
        "email": "siniscalchi88@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Luisa Siniscalchi",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Ivan Visconti",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Publicly Verifiable Zero-Knowledge proofs are known to exist only from setup assumptions\nsuch as a trusted Common Reference String (CRS) or a Random Oracle. Unfortunately, the\nformer requires a trusted party while the latter does not exist.\nBlockchains are distributed systems that already exist and provide certain security properties\n(under some honest majority assumption), hence, a natural recent research direction has been\nto use a blockchain as an alternative setup assumption.\nIn TCC 2017 Goyal and Goyal proposed a construction of a publicly verifiable zero-knowledge\n(pvZK) proof system for some proof-of-stake blockchains. The zero-knowledge property of their\nconstruction however relies on some additional and not fully specified assumptions about the\ncurrent and future behavior of honest blockchain players.\nIn this paper, we provide several contributions. First, we show that when using a blockchain to\ndesign a provably secure protocol, it is dangerous to rely on demanding additional requirements\non behaviors of the blockchain players. We do so by showing an “attack of the clones” whereby\na malicious verifier can use a smart contract to slyly (not through bribing) clone capabilities of\nhonest stakeholders and use those to invalidate the zero-knowledge property of the proof system\nby Goyal and Goyal.\nSecond, we propose a new publicly verifiable zero-knowledge proof system that relies on non-interactive commitments and on an assumption on the min-entropy of some blocks appearing on the blockchain.\nThird, motivated by the fact that blockchains are a recent innovation and their resilience\nin the long run is still controversial, we introduce the concept of collapsing blockchain, and we\nprove that the zero-knowledge property of our scheme holds even if the blockchain eventually\nbecomes insecure and all blockchain players eventually become dishonest.",
    "keywords": [
      "publicly verifiable zero-knowledge",
      "(collapsing) blockchain",
      "smart contract"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
    "publication_info": "A minor revision of an IACR publication in PKC 2021",
    "last_updated": "2021-04-16",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
